{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox Cave | name =Khambhalida Caves | photo =Khambhalida Buddhist caves Gujarat.jpg | photo_caption =Khambhalida Buddhist caves, Gujarat. | location = | depth = | length = | map = India#India Gujarat |relief=yes | map_width = | map_caption = Location in Gujarat | label = Khambhalida Caves | map_alt = | coords = {{coord|display=inline, title|region:IN_type:landmark}} | survey = | survey_format = | discovery = | geology = | entrance_count = | entrance_list = | difficulty = | hazards = | access = | translation = | language = | pronunciation = }} {{BuddhasHolySites}} '''Khambhalida Caves''', or '''Rajkot Caves''', are three Buddhist caves located near [[Gondal, Gujarat|Gondal]] in [[Rajkot district]], [[Gujarat]], [[India]].
==Architecture== P. P. Pandya, a prominent archeologist, discovered these Buddhist caves in 1958. These caves are maintained by the Archaeology Department of Gujarat state.
The caves are situated at the foot of small hillocks on the banks of a spring. They are carved out of [[limestone]] rocks. There are three caves, the central one contains the ''[[stupa]]'' which is known as ''chaitya'' cave. There are two sculptures of [[Bodhisattva]] on the either sides of the gate of the ''chaitya'' cave. On the left, the figure is probably [[Padmapani]] under [[Ashoka]]-like tree with a female companion and five attendants. There is a [[yaksha]]-like dwarf on the left of it holding a basket. The figure on the right is probably [[Vajrapani]] under Ashoka-like tree with similar attendants. The broad belts of female are similar to that of figures at [[Uparkot Caves]] of Junagadh. They are comparable to late [[Kushana]]-[[Western Satraps|Kshatapa]] period sculptures elsewhere as well as features some late Andhra mannerism.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Nanavati|first=J. M.|last2=Dhaky|first2=M. A.|date=1969-01-01|title=The Maitraka and the Saindhava Temples of Gujarat|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.321094|journal=Artibus Asiae. Supplementum|volume=26|pages=15–17|doi=10.2307/1522666}}</ref> The caves are believed to have come into existence in the 4th or 5th century AD.<ref name="Gujarat Tourism">{{cite web|last=Tourism Corporation of Gujarat Limited |title=Khambhalida Caves |url=http://www.gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=166&webpartid=1690 |publisher=Gujarat Tourism, Govt. of Gujarat |accessdate=1 December 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111127061525/http://www.gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=166&webpartid=1690 |archivedate=27 November 2011 |df= }}</ref>
The another cave on the left is deep and huge and is open in the front. It may have used for meditation by the monks.<ref name=":0"/><ref>http://www.discoveredindia.com/gujarat/attractions/caves/khambhalid-caves-rajkot.htm</ref>
There are 15 small caves situated near the Khambhalida caves. They are probably carved by the [[Lesser Vehicle]] branch of Buddhism.{{cn|date=October 2017}}
<gallery> Buddha Caves in Rajkot District.jpg|The caves Khambhalida Buddhist Caves.jpg|The caves </gallery>
==Other information== A modern large Buddhist temple complex is coming up near by.
It is said that for centuries Gir Forest extended till Khambhalida Village.
