'''Mullá 'Alí-i-Bastámí''' (died 1846) was the second [[Letters of the Living|Letter of the Living]] in the [[Bábís|Bábí]] movement. He is also probably the first and one of the best known martyrs of the early Bábí period.{{sfn|Momen|2009}}{{sfn|Winters|1997}}
== Biography ==
=== Early Life === He was born near the small city of [[Bastam]] in northwestern [[Persian Empire|Persia]] during the reign of the [[Qajar dynasty]].{{sfn|Amanat|1989|p=212}} He married in his youth and had at least one child.{{Sfn|Momen|1982|p=}} As a young man gained a reputation for his interest in religion and studied as a [[Mullah]] in the shrine city of [[Mashhad]] as a young man.
In Mashhad he became familiar with local clerics who were associated with the [[Millenarianism|millenarian]] [[Shaykhism|Shaykhí]] denomination of [[Shia Islam]] and was attracted to Shaykhí doctrine.{{Sfn|Amanat|1989|p=176}} Eventually he moved to [[Karbala]] in the [[Ottoman Empire]] and studied under [[Kazim Rashti|Siyyid Kazim Rashti]] then the leader of Shaykhism for at least seven years.
=== Conversion to Bábism === Shaykis expected the imminent arrival of the [[Al-Qa'im (person)|Qa'im]] or [[Mahdi]], and after the death of Siyyid Kazim in January 1844,{{sfn|Momen|1982}} Bastámí led a group of Shaykhís who—along with a group led by [[Mullá Husayn]] sought out the expected Mahdi. {{sfn|Amanat|1989|p=176}} On May 22nd, 1844 Mullá Husayn became the first Shayki to accept a [[Shiraz|Shirazi]] merchant named [[Báb|Siyyid ʿAli Muhammad]] as the Mahdi predicted in [[Islamic eschatology]]; Bastámí reportedly converted rapidly after hearing some verses of the [[Selections from the Writings of the Báb|Qayyúmu'l-Asmá']] written by Ali Muhammad.{{sfn|Amanat|1989|p=176}} ʿAli Muhammad would later take on the title of the Báb, meaning "gate" in Arabic and declare himself to be a [[Manifestation of God]] founding the new religion of [[Bábism]]. Bastámí accepted the Báb as the Mahdi on their first meeting and was appointed by him to the position of one of eighteen [[Letters of the Living]] and identified as the allegorical return of the Shia [[Ali|Imam 'Ali]].{{sfn|Amanat|1989|p=176}} Most sources identify him as the second Letter of the Living, but a minority say he was the fourth. A [[Tablet (religious)|tablet]] was addressed by the Báb to each of the Letters of the Living, including Bastámí; no translation of this tablet into English exists at present.
=== Trial in Baghdad === The Báb gave Bastámí the very specific mission of leaving Persia and travelling to the holy [[Shi'a]] shrine cities of [[Najaf]] and Karbala in modern-day Iraq about the summer of 1844.<ref>[http://bahai-library.com/chronology_principal_events_dawn-breakers Chronology of Principal Events Related in the Dawn-Breakers], Bahai-library.com</ref> It was here he was to announce the Báb's mission to [[Ijtihad|mujtahid]] Shaykh Muhammad Hasan,{{sfn|Momen|2009}} a senior member of the Shi'a clergy. He was put on trial for heresy on the basis of a copy of the [[Qayyúmu'l-Asmá']] in his possession on 13 January 1845 by a combined jury of Shi'a and Sunni clerics.{{sfn|Momen|2009}} The trial spun into a political event pitting Ottoman/Sunni interests against Shi'a/Persian interests - the Sunni clergy wanted Bastamí to be immediately executed while the Shi'a clergy insisted only on banishment and Persian politicians requested his removal to Persia.{{sfn|Momen|2009}} Instead, in April, he was transferred to Istanbul where he was further sentenced to hard labour in Istanbul's docks.{{sfn|Momen|2009}} Persian politicians continued insisting but when the Ottoman's finally agreed, 4 December 1846, it was found he had died a few days later and was accounted to be the first Bábi martyr by Bábis and Bahá'ís.{{sfn|Momen|2009}} After his death a [[Ziyarat|visitation prayer]] was revealed by the Báb in his honor.{{sfn|MacEoin|1994|p=27}}
